This paper deals with the problem of computing approximate Nash equilibria in games, which is a central topic in game theory and algorithmic game theory. The paper specifically focuses on symmetric bimatrix games, which are a well-studied class of games in game theory. Therefore, cs.GT (Game Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a polynomial-time algorithm, which involves computational techniques and optimization, indicating that it could also be relevant to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Additionally, the paper involves the analysis of the computational complexity of the algorithm, which suggests that it could be relevant to cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the paper deals with approximation algorithms, which is a topic in machine learning and optimization, indicating that it could also be relevant to cs.LG (Machine Learning).
